            <h3>Why it has to be in person</h3>
            <p>Most security services are remote. A technician connects from another city, applies configurations they can't fully audit in your environment, and leaves a service portal open behind them. The moment anyone holds remote access to your device — even to protect it — your threat model is already broken. A backdoor for a security provider is a backdoor for anyone.</p>
            <p>Here the method is different. Hardening is applied in your presence, on your timeline, with hardware you keep. Nothing enters your devices that you haven't seen; nothing leaves your hands. No remote tools, no cloud, no logs, no app — at any point, for any reason.</p>

            <h3>How it works</h3>
            <ul class="principles">
                <li>Every engagement starts from your specific threat — not a generic checklist.</li>
                <li>Nothing leaves your presence. No remote tools, no cloud, no third parties.</li>
                <li>One point of contact, from the first assessment to the Certificate of Hardening — directly.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Why Dr. Tabansky</h3>
            <p>The standards applied here — NSA endpoint guidance, the NIST SP 800-series, NCSC device security — are the same frameworks trusted by government agencies and global enterprises. Dr. Tabansky has spent two decades advising governments and agencies on cyber operations across Israel, Asia, Europe, and Africa. That experience shapes every engagement: the threat assessment, the hardening sequence, the hardware, and the Certificate delivered at the end.</p>
            <p>The full record — publications, academic positions, media — is public, so you can verify, independently, that this is someone who has operated at the level the work requires.</p>
